Let \mathcal {A} be a path object. Any left-cloven family of path objects \mathcal {B}\colon  
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\to  \mathsf {PathObj} gives rise to a canonical displayed path object over \mathcal {A} in which:

fr:ol.fr:li:
for x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
 and b:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} x\right \rvert \mathclose {}
, the identity element \mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {B}}{x}\colon  b \approx _{\mathcal {B}}^{\mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{x}}b is given by the component \Phi _{\mathcal {B}} xb\colon  
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{x}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
_*b\approx _{\mathcal {B} x}{b} of the unit law of the given right cleaving of \mathcal {B}.
